{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/delirium/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"2b925b35-d493-5d01-bb58-9f18c37e1357","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 011b03c4-a49d-4b67-8e12-e0af03e02955 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field 011b03c4-a49d-4b67-8e12-e0af03e02955 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f861d956-8427-44ac-89b7-b374148c8367 --><!-- begin field 70227f8a-5f2a-4987-8963-bb9c88fe8ac1 --><ul><li><strong>Delirium (sometimes called 'acute confusional state')</strong> is an acute, fluctuating syndrome of disturbed consciousness, attention, cognition and perception [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">NICE, 2010a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Inouye, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Kalish, 2014</a>].<ul><li>Delirium usually develops over hours to days and behavioural disturbance, personality changes, and psychotic features may occur [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Australian and New Zealand Society for Geriatric Medicine, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">NICE, 2015b</a>].</li></ul></li><li>Delirium typically occurs in people with <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/background-information/predisposing-factors/\">predisposing factors</a> (such as advanced age or multiple comorbidities) when new <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/background-information/precipitating-factors/\">precipitating factors</a> (such as some medications or infection) are added [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Vidal, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Kalish, 2014</a>].</li><li>Delirium can be classified into 3 subtypes based on the person's symptoms [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Vidal, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2015</a>]:<ul><li><strong>Hyperactive delirium</strong> — may present with inappropriate behaviour, hallucinations, or agitation. Restlessness and wandering are common [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Australian and New Zealand Society for Geriatric Medicine, 2012</a>].</li><li><strong>Hypoactive delirium</strong> — may present with lethargy, reduced concentration, and appetite. The person may appear quiet or withdrawn [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Australian and New Zealand Society for Geriatric Medicine, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">NICE Pathway, 2014</a>].</li><li><strong>Mixed delirium</strong> — signs and symptoms of both hyperactive and hypoactive subtypes are present.</li></ul></li><li>The pathophysiology of delirium is not fully understood, and multiple mechanisms (including cholinergic deficiency, dopaminergic excess, and inflammation) may contribute to its development [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/delirium/references/\">Inouye, 2014</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field 70227f8a-5f2a-4987-8963-bb9c88fe8ac1 --><!-- end item f861d956-8427-44ac-89b7-b374148c8367 -->","topic":{"id":"6b89f111-d1d1-510e-8846-71e15c389f06","topicId":"64430de8-33e7-409d-b433-725a712a6f41","topicName":"Delirium","slug":"delirium","lastRevised":"Last revised in April 2020","chapt